On September 11, 2020, President Donald Trump announced a historic agreement between Israel and Bahrain. The leaders of both countries expressed condolences for the September 11th attacks and agreed to fully normalize diplomatic relations. The agreement includes exchanging embassies and ambassadors, establishing direct flights, and initiating cooperation in various sectors such as health, business, technology, education, security, and agriculture. This is the second peace agreement involving Israel in the last month, following the agreement with the United Arab Emirates. Trump expressed hope that more countries would join in the future, leading to stability, security, and prosperity in the Middle East. The President also discussed the positive changes in the Middle East, including the fight against terrorism and the potential for positive developments with Iran and the Palestinians. Various members of the administration praised Trump's leadership and the historic nature of the agreement.